sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: F plasmid
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: F plasmid backbone with BioBrick sites removed.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Reshma Shetty
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This is a (near) single copy origin derived from the F plasmid. The naturally occurring BioBricks sites were removed with an intent to preserve the amino acid and codon frequency where possible. Similar to the pSMART VC sequence from Lucigen http://www.lucigen.com/products/Cloning_Systems/CopyRight.html. It is intended to be combined with other vector components (antibiotic resistance marker, multiple cloning site) in order to form a BioBricks vector. Relevant information can be found at http://openwetware.org/wiki/BioBrick_Parts_for_Plasmid_Engineering.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: pUC19 ori
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Minimal pUC19-derived high copy replication origin
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Reshma Shetty
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: High copy origin of replication derived from pSB1A3. Designed to omit antibiotic resistance markers and primer binding sites. Lacks mutations that render BBa_I50020 nonfunctional as a replication origin.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: We had to leave several restriction sites in because point mutations that eliminated these sites were found to render the origin nonfunctional.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: pSC101
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Reshma Shetty
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: pSC101 origin of replication which is supposed to have low copy number. This was the origin used in Michael Elowitz's repressilator and in Bujard's pZS4Int-1 vector with mutations introduced to eliminate a SpeI site. It is also the origin of replication in pSB4* series plasmids.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: The replication origin boundaries were chosen quite liberally (i.e. they might include more sequence than is strictly necessary) because a different version of this origin (BBa_I50040) was shown to be non-functional.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: This part was amplified from pSB4A3-P1010.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K533000
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: ZHANG Yunxiao
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
p15A replication origin belongs to a different compatibility group from the common pMB1 (pBR or pUC) origin, and hence allows for co-existence with other pUC origin plasmids.
When using this part, ligate it along with a proper antibiotic resistance gene and your gene of interest together to make a circular plasmid. Please do NOT include any other replication origin in your design.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: Unlike pMB1 origin, which allows for chloramphenicol amplification, p15A replication origin is insensitive to chloramphenicol and remains in low copy number. This replication origin is different from the original one in that it contains several mutations, which increases the copy number to be no lower than pBR origin. In this way, both the compatibility and the convenience for use are accommodated.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: OriV
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Margaret Ruzicka
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Plasmids containing oriV and the corresponding Rep proteins (from RSF1010) are autonomously replicated in a broad range of hosts. It has been reported that RSF1010 derived plasmids containing oriV and the Rep proteins are stably maintained in Pseudomonas (Bagdasarian 1981), Caulobacter (Umelo-Njaka et al. 2001), Erwinia, Serratia (Leemans 1987), and several cyanobacteria strains (Mermet-Bouvier 1993) including Synechocystis PCC6803 and PCC6714 and Synechococcus PCC7942 and PCC6301.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: This part is to be constructed with the Rep proteins derived from an RSF1010 plasmid.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: This part is taken from the RSF1010 derived plasmid pRL1383a. A description of this plasmid can be found at the NCBI database at accession number AF403426.
